         <h1>Lowell Perry, 69, Football Star and Ford Aide </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Lowell Perry , an all-American receiver at the University of Michigan , the first black assistant coach in the National Football League 's modern era and the chairman of the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission in the Ford administration , died Sunday at a hospital in Southfield , Mich . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 69 . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was cancer , his family said . <br><blue>4</blue>Perry was a sure-handed and speedy offensive end , a safety on defense and a punt returner for Michigan from 1950 to 1952 , and he played on the team that defeated California in the 1951 Rose Bowl . <br><blue>5</blue>Joining the Pittsburgh Steelers in 1956 after playing football in the Army , he emerged as an outstanding receiver and kick returner . <br><blue>6</blue>But in the season 's sixth game he suffered a fractured pelvis and dislocated hip when hit by the Giants ' star tackle , Roosevelt Grier , while carrying the ball on a reverse play . <br><blue>7</blue>During a 13-week hospital stay , Perry was visited by Art Rooney , the Steeler owner . '' <br><blue>8</blue>He told me , ' Lowell , as long as I own the Pittsburgh Steelers , you have a job in my organization , ' '' Perry remembered . <br><blue>9</blue>The following season , Perry became the Steelers ' receivers coach . <br><blue>10</blue>The N.F.L. had a black head coach , Fritz Pollard , the former Brown University star , in the 1920 's . <br><blue>11</blue>But until Perry , there had been no black coaches since World War II . <br><blue>12</blue>Perry coached with the Steelers for one season , then left to complete studies toward a degree at the Detroit College of Law . <br><blue>13</blue>In 1966 , he became the first black to serve as an N.F.L. broadcaster when he was hired by CBS as an analyst . <br><blue>14</blue>He became a board member of N.F.L. Charities , a league foundation . <br><blue>15</blue>After serving as a lawyer with the National Labor Relations Board , Perry joined the Chrysler Corporation as a labor relations lawyer in 1963 . <br><blue>16</blue>He was a leading member of Chrysler 's management team in negotiations with the United Auto Workers on a national contract in 1971 and later managed Chrysler plants in Michigan . <br><blue>17</blue>Perry was named by President Gerald R. Ford in May 1975 to run the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission , the agency responsible for enforcing anti-discrimination laws governing private employers . <br><blue>18</blue>Having taken over an agency with a backlog of 100,000 complaints and five previous chairmen in its decade-long existence , Perry faced continued managerial problems . <br><blue>19</blue>He resigned after 12 months and returned to Chrysler , remaining there until retiring in 1980 . <br><blue>20</blue>He served during the 1990 's as the director of Michigan 's labor department and Office of Urban Programs . <br><hr><br><blue>1(3)</blue>: <m_str>I</m_str> (8_11) 	<m_str>me</m_str> (8_3) 	<m_str>my</m_str> (8_22) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>the season 's</m_str> (6_3) 	<m_str>The following season</m_str> (9_1) 	<br><blue>3(3)</blue>: <m_str>Michigan</m_str> (4_19) 	<m_str>Michigan</m_str> (16_30) 	<m_str>Michigan 's</m_str> (20_11) 	<br><blue>4(3)</blue>: <m_str>the Chrysler Corporation</m_str> (15_15) 	<m_str>Chrysler 's</m_str> (16_7) 	<m_str>Chrysler</m_str> (16_27) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>The N.F.L.</m_str> (10_1) 	<m_str>the 1920 's</m_str> (10_19) 	<br><blue>6(23)</blue>: <m_str>He</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>Perry</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>Perry</m_str> (18_21) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>Perry</m_str> (15_13) 	<m_str>Perry</m_str> (12_1) 	<m_str>Lowell</m_str> (8_6) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (20_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (4_26) 	<m_str>Perry</m_str> (9_5) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (13_4) 	<m_str>Perry</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (5_14) 	<m_str>Perry</m_str> (8_27) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (13_16) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_8) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (14_1) 	<m